i## When We Don't Have Enough ROM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut in the later stage of the project, we found that the 64 KB ROM of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSTM32F103C8T6 is no longer enough for us. The ROM space is mainly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioccupied by the following parts:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- BME680's closed source BSEC library		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - BSEC is the only source of BME680's TVOC reading. The sensor only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    provides a resistor value, and there is no simple formula to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    convert resistor value to actual TVOC readings.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Floating-point logic of `printf` and `scanf`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - InfluxDB, what we use, accepts only ASCII-formatted upload data,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    so the IEEE 754 floating-point readings from sensors must be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    converted to ASCII text.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - For the same reason, the latitude and longitude information must		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    be extracted from the GPS module's NMEA0183 statements and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    converted to IEEE 754 floating-point numbers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- STM32's library functions		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Those responsible for register operations.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore we tried to shrink the code size in these places:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- For BME680, while we cannot modify the closed source library itself,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  we greatly reduced the size of the logic that calls the library.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- For GPS, instead of conversion to/from floating-point numbers, we		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  chose to simply copy the latitude/longitude text from NMEA0183		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  statements.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - A NMEA0183 statement that involves latitude and longitude is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    formatted as follow:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - `$GNGGA,hhmmss.ss,llll.ll,a,yyyyy.yy,a,x,xx,x.x,x.x,M,x.x,M,x.x,xxxx*hh`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - `$GNGGA,074023.000,1234.56789,N,12345.67891,E,1,13,0.9,32.3,M,0.0,M,,*46`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Separated by comma, each field represents (from left to right):		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - `$GNGGA` means that this statement contains latitude and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      longitude information		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 2nd column is the current time		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The time above is AM 07:40:23, in UTC timezone		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 3rd column is latitude, in format `degree * 100 + minute`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The latitude above is 12 degrees, 34.56789 minutes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 4th column represents north/south of the equator		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The number in the third column is always positive, no matter		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        north/south of the equator		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 5th column is longitude, still in format `degree * 100 + minute`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The longitude above is 123 degrees, 45.67891 minutes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 6th column is east/west of the prime meridian		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The number in the fifth column is also always positive, no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        matter east/west of the prime meridian		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - We don't care about the rest information		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Here is our logic:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Copy the third column to the latitude character array,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      **starting from the second character of the array**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If the 4th column is N (north of the equator), set the first		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      character of the array to `0`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Result has format 01234.56789, can be recognized by InfluxDB		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If the 4th column is S (south of the equator), set the first		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      character of the array to `-` (minus sign)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Result has format -1234.56789, can also be recognized by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        InfluxDB		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Do the same to longitude data in columns 5 and 6		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - For conversion from `degree * 100 + minute` to more commonly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      used `degree`, we choose to do it on the more powerful server		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- For STM32 library functions, we can switch to LL library for the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  parts we don't need to directly operate on (ex. frequency setup done		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  automatically by STM32CubeMX)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - STM32 provide 2 different sets of library functions for each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    component, HAL and LL		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - HAL is more abstracted and easier to use but takes more space		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - LL is closer to register manipulations, small yet difficult to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - In `Project Manager - Advanced Settings`, switching RCC (frequency		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    setup) to LL saves a few kilobytes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- For standard library functions, if multiple functions are doing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  similar things, try to use only one of them		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Ex. if you use `printf` and `sprintf` together, you may replace		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    `printf` with a combination of `sprintf` and `HAL_UART_Transmit`;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    saves quite some space		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Remember to turn on compiler optimizations and disable debugging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Set `DEBUG = 0` and `OPT = -Os` in Makefile		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - By the way, for STM32's `printf` to support floating-point		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    numbers, you need to add `-u _printf_float` in `LDFLAGS` in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    Makefile to enable that support		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
