i# Logging on to School Wi-Fi		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Sensors Need to Connect to School Wi-Fi		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iMy school provides 2 Wi-Fi networks:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. One is an open network (no password), and a login page with HTTPS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   encryption will pop up after connecting to it, where you enter your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   username and password to log in.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. The other is eduroam that authenticates with WPA2 enterprise mode.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter research on the capabilities of ESP8266 Wi-Fi module, I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconcluded that:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. ESP8266 comes with an AT firmware by default, where we connect to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Wi-Fi networks via serial port commands.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - In this case, it only supports open networks and WPA2 personal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     networks, but not eduroam, which uses WPA2 enterprise.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - But there is no room left in STM32 for HTTPS encryption		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     libraries, which means we cannot submit credentials to log in.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. ESP8266 can be reprogrammed with custom code.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - But finding the official SDK of ESP8266 along with documentation		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     is a bit hard.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Although ESP8266 supports the Arduino platform, it still doesn't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     include an SSL encryption library.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - In addition, ESP8266 only supports PAP-encrypted WPA2 enterprise		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     networks, while my school uses MSCHAPv2.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe solution is kind of a cheat: I went through the code on my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iRaspberry Pi and found a login script to the school network. Back when		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI wrote that script, the login page wasn't using HTTPS, and what I was		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isending was a plain HTTP request. I tested it and found out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isurprisingly that it still works!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe final solution is: STM32 instructs ESP8266 to connect to that open		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork via AT commands, and also sends HTTP request via AT commands		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito simulate a login attempt. In this case, one less program needs to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe coded.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Can't you set up a Wi-Fi access point with a router?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Well, you can't put a router around every sensor, can you?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
