i# Obtaining Sensor Data		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## BME680		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn our program, BME680 is solely controlled by its closed source BSEC		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibrary. However, BSEC only supports measurements every 30 seconds or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i300 seconds; if that interval is incorrect, BSEC will neither perform		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imeasurements nor return valid data.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut since BSEC relies on us to provide timing and communication		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifunctions, we made a dangerous move: decoupling the BSEC timing from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe actual system time. Specifically, when we run BSEC every 15		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iminutes, instead of telling it 15 minutes has passed, we tell it that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionly 300 seconds has passed, or it's exactly the time for the next		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imeasurement, to force BSEC to do its job.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## PMS5003		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPMS5003 is quite simple to use. Simply pull the enable signal high to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iturn on its fan - wait 30 seconds - and read data from the serial		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iport.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPMS5003 sends 32 bytes of data each time, with a fixed packet header		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand a checksum of the whole packet. To avoid reading only half of a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipacket, thanks to the characteristic of PMS5003 sending data every		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isecond, we did the following:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. First, try to read 32 bytes from the serial port within 100 ms. If		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   it succeeds, it means the PMS5003 happens to be sending data right		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   now.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. If the data read the first time is not full 32 bytes, try to read		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   again, but with a time limit of 2 seconds. We are effectively		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   waiting for PMS5003 to send its next packet of data.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Then verify the data with checksumming and parse it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## MiCS6814		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iMiCS6814 is the most difficult sensor to be used in our project. Since		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit is manufactured with micro-nano fabrication and represents		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipollutant gas concentration with resistance, every individual sensor		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imodule behaves differently to gases, has different resistance under		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe same concentration of gas, and has different slopes of resistance		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhen concentration changes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDue to the limitation of available devices, we had to assume that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithere wouldn't be major changes in gas concentrations and ignore the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idifference of slope of resistance. For resistance differences under		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe same condition, we swapped the fixed value voltage divider		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresistor to a potentiometer (variable resistor). Now instead of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icalculating absolute resistance values, the program computes the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresistance ratio to the reference value (resistance of the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipotentiometer). Then, put all devices in the same environment, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iadjust the potentiometers (and their readings in turn) with reference		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito weather reports and professional devices, so that they have the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isame reading.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
