i## Battery Status and Voltage		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i18650 lithium batteries usually have a voltage range of around		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3.0-4.5V (not exact), which is above the 3.3V input voltage limit of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSTM32. Therefore two resistors are needed to divide the voltage, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe result is connected to STM32's ADC.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSTM32 can also monitor the input voltage to the chip since it has an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinternal stable 1.2V power source connected to ADC. Since ADC readings		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iare relative to the chip input voltage, the input voltage can be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icalculated back from the reading on this power source.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSTM32 also has a built-in temperature sensor, which represents values		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwith ADC readings. However, the temperature sensor on STM32F103C8T6 is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inot calibrated and is vastly different from the actual temperature,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand as we already have BME680, this sensor is kind of useless for us.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## One More Thing on STM32 ADC		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnother thing about STM32F103C8T6's ADC is that if it needs to read in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imultiple inputs at the same time, a plain `HAL_ADC_Start` won't work,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand DMA is a must.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDMA, or direct memory access, tells peripherals to write data directly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito a specified position in memory, with no help from the CPU. DMA can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe used to reduce CPU usage or implement continuous sampling.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCorresponding DMA channels need to be added in the DMA Settings tab on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe ADC page of STM32CubeMX to be used.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut since we don't need continuous sampling, we can set a "sample		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomplete" flag after receiving the interrupt in the DMA's interrupt		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihandler (usually in `stm32f1xx_it.c`). Now when the program is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irunning, it first calls `HAL_ADC_Start_DMA` to start sampling, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithen repeatedly checks the flag until the task is complete, and call		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`HAL_ADC_Stop_DMA` to stop. If you're brave enough, you may live		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwithout that flag and simply do a delay.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# One Week Battery Life		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## STM32 Low Power Consumption Mode		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOur device needs to sample data every 15 minutes with the battery as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe power source and continuously run for a week. This poses a high		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irequirement for its power consumption in sleep mode.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTo reach that goal, we need to switch STM32 and sensors to either low		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipower consumption mode or off position.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- According to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [Datasheet](https://www.st.com/resource/en/datasheet/stm32f103c8.pdf),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  STM32F103C8T6 has 3 different low power modes:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - SLEEP mode, where only CPU is switched off, peripherals such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    ADC, I2C, and UART are still running.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 5.5 mA at 8 MHz, obviously too high		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - STOP mode, where CPU and most of the peripherals are off, but RAM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    and registers are retained and can be woken up via RTC or external		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    interrupt.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 13.5 uA, acceptable moderate power consumption (little enough		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      compared to other modules)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Easy programming with almost no special handling		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - STANDBY mode, where CPU and peripherals are off, RAM and registers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    are cleared.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Program runs from the beginning every time, so status has to be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      recorded in ROM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - 2.4 uA, lowest, but difficult to code for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- We chose STOP mode at last, with a few notes:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Enable RTC's `Clock Source` (turn on its functionality).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Set `RTC OUT` to `No RTC Output`, or turn on its output without		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    pin mapping.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - In this case, the RTC output is connected to an interrupt		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      controller, so when a specific time is reached, an interrupt		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      will be triggered, and the CPU will be turned back on.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If you don't do this (set to `Disable`), STM32's CPU will never		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      wake up again.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Enable `RTC alarm interrupt through EXTI line` in `NVIC Settings`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    below.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Let the CPU accept RTC interrupts, or the CPU will also sleep		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      forever.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - When calling such functionality, first reset the time of RTC (out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    of safety), then set the alarm, and finally enter low power mode.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - RTC only has a precision of 1 second.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere is an example code snippet of sleep and timed wake up:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```c		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivoid deep_sleep(uint32_t seconds) {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    RTC_TimeTypeDef rtc_time = {0, 0, 0};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    RTC_AlarmTypeDef rtc_alarm = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            seconds / 3600,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            (seconds % 3600) / 60,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            seconds % 60		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        },		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        RTC_ALARM_A		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_RTC_SetTime(&hrtc, &rtc_time, RTC_FORMAT_BIN);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_RTC_SetAlarm_IT(&hrtc, &rtc_alarm, RTC_FORMAT_BIN);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    __HAL_PWR_CLEAR_FLAG(PWR_FLAG_WU);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_PWR_EnterSTOPMode(PWR_LOWPOWERREGULATOR_ON, PWR_STOPENTRY_WFI);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Turning Off External Modules		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTurning off PMS5003 and ESP8266 is easy since they both have a pin to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontrol power status. When that pin is pulled low, they will both		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iautomatically enter the hibernate mode, with a few microamps of power		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconsumption.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTurning of BME680 is also easy, which is done by BSEC.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut neither ATGM336H nor MiCS6814 has built-in power control, and they		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwill continuously run and consume a lot of power. Therefore an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexternal switch is needed to cut their power.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iInitially, we planned to use an N-channel MOSFET to cut the power:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
IMOSFET Power Switching Circuit	/usr/uploads/202006/circuit-mosfet.png	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCTL in the schematic represents the digital output of STM32, and R1 is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe corresponding module. When CTL outputs 0, MOSFET M1 will cut the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icircuit to turn off R1 and vice versa.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut in our testing, when the STM32 outputs 1, its output voltage 3.3V		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis not enough for the MOSFET to turn on completely. The MOSFET still		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihas a resistance of around 30Ω, which divides too much voltage away,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand the module cannot obtain enough power to work normally.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSo we added a BJT triode to pull the digital output to 5V:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
IPower Switching Circuit with BJT Triode	/usr/uploads/202006/circuit-bjt.png	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen STM32 outputs 1, triode Q1 lets current through and pulls low the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontrol voltage of MOSFET, turning off the modules; when STM32 outputs		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0, Q1 cuts power, the control voltage of MOSFET is pulled high to 5V		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iby R2, and the module is turned on normally. Note that the STM32		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioutput is inverted from the module's power state.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSome stores on Taobao sell power level shifters that uses 2 levels of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresistors and triodes to correct the inversion; but we don't care		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iabout this, as it's a simple modification of the program.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut in our testing, the circuit consumed a lot of power, up to 50 mA		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhen power is cut off. Closer inspection reveals that the BJT triode		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipulls the STM32 output to as low as 0.8V, and the output is almost in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia "shorted" state, outputting a large current.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe solution is an additional resistor for limiting current, R3, in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe following schematic:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
IPower Switching Circuit with BJT Triode and Resistor	/usr/uploads/202006/circuit-bjt-resistor.png	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> So STM32 can work normally while outputting 50 mA...		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Keeping Power Supply On		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe MH-CD42 power module is originally designed as a battery		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanagement module for power banks. One of its functionality is to turn		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioff the power output when no devices are connected. MH-CD42 measures		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe output current, and when the current is below 45 mA for around 30		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iseconds, it turns off automatically.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFor power bank users, this is a useful feature, but for us with a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isleep mode current of a few mA, this functionality greatly interferes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwith normal operation. What's more complicated is that, since MH-CD42		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis a highly integrated module, there is no power pin we can forcefully		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipull up to keep the power on.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWe first searched for the datasheet of MH-CD42 but almost found no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuseful information. But we did find		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[a post on MH-CD42](https://techobsessed.net/tag/mh-cd42/), in which		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe author found that the MH-CD42 module has the same external circuit		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ias another IP5306 chip and confirmed that they have equivalent		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifunctionality.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[This post (Chinese)](https://www.jianshu.com/p/25fa6ec89953)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iintroduces a way to keep the output of IP5306 on, specifically to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconnect an output of the MCU to the button of the power module, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isend a low signal every ten seconds. It simulates pressing the power		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibutton every few seconds and keeps the power on.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSo we soldered a wire from STM32 to the soldering pad on the power		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imodule, and wrote some code:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```c		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifor(size_t i = 0; i < 85; i++) {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    deep_sleep(10);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOB, GPIO_PIN_5, GPIO_PIN_RESET);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_Delay(500);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    HAL_GPIO_WritePin(GPIOB, GPIO_PIN_5, GPIO_PIN_SET);		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iEach loop takes 10.5 seconds, and at 85 loops the total time is around		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i15 minutes or 900 seconds. In each loop, STM32 stays in low power STOP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imode for 10 seconds, and wakes up in the other 500 ms.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
