i## Communicating with ESP8266		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe AT instruction manual of ESP8266 is a bit difficult to find, but		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[we did it finally](https://www.itead.cc/wiki/images/5/53/Esp8266_at_instruction_set_en_v1.5.4_0.pdf).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWe need a few instructions:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `ATE0` turns off echoing of commands. This simplifies parsing of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  results and reduces the amount of data transferred (thus reducing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  latency)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+CWMODE=1` sets ESP8266 to Wi-Fi client mode		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+CWJAP_CUR="SchoolWiFi",""` connects ESP8266 to open Wi-Fi		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  network without password		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+CIPSTART="TCP","influxdb.lantian.pub",8086` creates a TCP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  connection to specified host and port		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+CIPSEND=123` sends 123 bytes of data		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+CIPCLOSE` closes connection		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `AT+GSLP=2147483647` enter a long sleep (until the next "enable"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  signal)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iA few points to remember:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- ESP8266 commands end with Windows CRLF `\r\n`, but some serial		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  communication software in Linux sends `\n` when pressing enter. In		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  this case, the command will not be executed correctly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- All the commands above need ESP8266 to respond with OK to work, so		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
